Is there a recommended way to handle cases where there's an error not related to any specific field. For example, async submission to the server failing due to no internet?

Or is it recommended to handle this independently of React Hook Form?

----

**Edit:** I had assumed that the first argument in `setError` needed to be a field name you're using, but I guess that's not actually the case. But I'm still a bit confused about how to integrate that with `formState` for this case where we're setting our own error message that shows at the end of the form using `const [msg, setMsg] = useState('')`

because if we call `setMsg('Failed to contact server')` it will immediately be overridden by the following

```js
useEffect(() => {
    if (formState.isSubmitted && !formState.isSubmitSuccessful) setMsg('Please fill out all required fields');
}, [formState]);
```

Ah, derp. Simple enough, I just changed the code to use `setError('server' {...})` and then:

```js
useEffect(() => {
    if (formState.isSubmitted && !formState.isSubmitSuccessful && !errors.server) setMsg('Please fill out all required fields');
}, [formState]);
```

@Slapbox @bluebill1049 what is the intended way to handle async submission errors? I was expecting something like this:

```js
const onSubmit = async (values) => {
    try {
        // ajax here
        window.alert('ok');
    } catch (error) {
        console.error(error);
        throw error;
    }
};

...

{ formState.isSubmitted && formState.isSubmitSuccessful === true && <p>Success</p> }
{ formState.isSubmitted && formState.isSubmitSuccessful === false && <p>Failure</p> }
```

Throwing in the main loop is of course a kamizake move. What is the indented flow? Should we use setError with a generic name? ie:
```js
setError("global", {
    type: "manual",
    message: "Submit failed because you suck"
});
```
